ACCIDENT:  K-COM TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST.  JETT EXPRESS VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WEST.  THE JETT EXPRESS DRIVER CROSSED OVER INTO K-COM LANE.  K-COM DRIVER WENT AS FAR RIGHT AS POSSIBLE.  JETT EXPRESS COLLIDED ALONG THE DRIVERS SIDE FROM FRONT TO BACK OF TRACTOR AND ROLL-OFF UNIT JETT EXPRESS TRACTOR CAUGHT ON FIRE AND WAS TOTALLY CONSUMED.

DRIVER WAS HEADED NORTHBOUND ON US 41 IN SCHERERVILLE, IN.  A PASSENGER CAR CUT IN FRONT OF HIM AND THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO SLAM ON HIS BRAKES.  BY DOING SO, THE LOAD INSIDE THE TRAILER SHIFTED AND THREE OF THE IBC CONTAINERS FELL OVER ON TOP OF EACH OTHER.  ONE OF THE CONTAINERS RUPTURED FROM THE IMPACT.  THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES AWAY BY AN OFFICER WHO SPOTTED THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED IN FRONT OF A STRIP MALL AREA WHICH WAS EVACUATED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND LAKE COUNTY HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAMS WERE NOTIFIED AND BROUGHT IN.  MISSAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONDUCTED THE CLEAN UP.  MAIN STREET WAS CLOSED TO TRAFFIC WHILE THE CLEAN UP WAS CONDUCTED, APPROXIMATELY 7 HOURS.

CARLOS TRANSPORTED THE WET PACKAGE BACK TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  DUE TO THE QUANTITY OF THE LEAKER, THE 5 GALLONS WERE NOT SOLIDIFIED, AND WERE ENTERED AS A DMN WITH LIQUID PRESENT.  THE LEAKED LIQUID ORIGINATED FROM THE CAP. AS THE PACKAGE TURNED OVER IN THE UPS HUB, A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKED OUT OF THE CAN AND WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARDBOARD.  THE CAP WAS FULLY TIGHTENED BUT WAS NOT CAPABLE OF SEALING THE CONTAINER.

OF CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE TO OVERSEE THE TRANSFER PROCESS.  TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING CARGO TANKER TO A NEW CARGO TANKER. DRUM WAS STRUCK AND PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED UPRIGHT TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SHIPPER TOOK THE DRUM BACK.

BAGS ARE TERRIBLE PACKAGES TYPES FOR LTL TRANSPORTATION.  THE LOADING AND UNLOADING OF THE FREIGHT SEVERAL TIMES RESULTS IN THE BAGS BEING RUBBED AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT AND THE WALLS OF THE TRAILER.  EXTRA CAUTION SHOULD HAVE BEEN USED DURING THE LOADING OF THIS PALLET AND DUNNAGE SHOULD HAVE BEEN USED TO PREVENT OTHER FREIGHT FROM RUBBING AGAINST THE BAGS.  ONE BAG WAS FOUND RIPPED.  THE MATERIALS WAS CLEANED UP, THE BAG WAS TAPED SHUT AND ALL THE MATERIAL INCLUDING THE RECOUPED MATERIALS WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE IN ROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE THERE WAS A LOAD SHIFT THAT RESULTED IN ONE OF THE CONTAINERS BEING CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  THE LOAD HAD LOAD BARS, BUT THE PALLET STILL FELL OVER.  THE STRETCH WRAPPING TECHNIQUE USED IS BEING REVIEWED AT THE LOADING FACILITY.  THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED BY OUR EPA RESPONSE TEAM AND THE WASTE WILL BE INCINERATED IN AN EPA APPROVED INCINERATOR.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND AIRCRAFT RELOAD WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  THE CULPRIT PACKAGE WAS LOADED INTO A ULD(REF:AMJ5449FX).  THIS ULD WAS THEN LOADED ONTO AN MD-11 AIRCRAFT (FLT-0004-MDM-CDG).  AFTER THE ULD WAS ONLOADED ONTO THE AIRCRAFT, LOADING PERSONNEL NOTICED AN ACRID, BURNING ODOR AND A SMOKY HAZE COMING FROM THE UNIT.  THE ULD WAS QUICKLY UNLOADED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND THE FEDEX FIRE DEPARTMENT UNIT (RURAL METRO) AS WELL AS THE MEMPHIS FIRE DEPARTMENT (MFD) WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  AFTER THE ULD WAS DOWN LOADED FIRE PERSONNEL APPROACHED THE UNIT TO OPEN THE VINYL CONTAINER CURTAIN.  AS THE CURTAIN WAS OPENED, A BACKDRAFT SITUATION OCCURRED CAUSING THE ALREADY SMOLDERING CULPRIT PACKAGE TO BURST INTO FLAMES.  THE FIRE IN THE ULD QUICKLY SPREAD TO A SIGNIFICANT NUMBER OF PACKAGES LOADED WITH THE CULPRIT PACKAGE.  THE FIRE ALSO CAUSED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE THAT THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED INTO.  THE COMBINED UNITS FROM FEDEX RURAL METRO AND MEMPHIS FIRE DEPARTMENT MOVED QUICKLY TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.  THE FIRE WAS DETERMINED AS HAVING STARTED IN THE CULPRIT PACKAGE CONTAINING TWO PROTOTYPE LITHIUM BATTERY PACK ASSEMBLIES.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT WALTER MCBURROWS/FAA/MEM AT 09:30(CST) 08/07/2004

column168: DRIVER STATES HE WAS DRIVING IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE AT A RATE OF APP 45 MPH THE AREA HAD 2 ON RAMPS.  HE WAS BETWEEN THEM.  2 TRUCKS AHEAD OF HIM LOCKED UP THEIR BRAKES.  HE DID ALSO TO PREVENT COLLISION.  WHEN HE DID THE CONTAINERS BENT THE LOAD BARS AND THE DRUMS SHIFTED FORWARD.  THEY HIT SOME 5 GAL. CONTAINERS AND BENT THEM CAUSING THE LIDS TO POP OFF AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED.  I SPOKE WITH THE DRIVER AND FIRE CHIEF. column168: AT 6:50 AM (CST) ON AUGUST 20, 2004, DURING A DAILY INSPECTION AT THE OES FACILITY IN PORT WASHINGTON, WI, LIQUID WAS IDENTIFIED BENEATH A TRUCK TRANSPORTING A 20-CUBIC YARD ROLL-OFF BOX OF F006 HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE LIQUID RELEASE FROM THE ROLL-OFF BOX COLLECTED ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE LIQUID WAS ABSORBED WITH CORN COB MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED IN A 30-GALLON POLY DRUM.  THE PAVEMENT WAS THEN DECONTAMINATED WITH A CHELATING SOLUTION OF EDTA.  THE CHELATING SOLUTION WAS THEN ABSORBED WITH CORN COB AND CONTAINERIZED INTO THE 30-GALLON POLY DRUM AS WELL.  THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH THE ORIGINAL GENERATOR OF THE WASTE MATERIAL TO INSURE THAT ONLY SOLID MATERIALS ARE PLACED INTO THE ROLL-OFF BOXES IN THE FUTURE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE RIGHT SIDE TRAILER WHEELS DROPPED OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE PAVEMENT CAUSING A HARD DRAG ON THE TRUCK.  WHEN THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE TRAILER BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT THE TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE AND SKIDDED ON THE PAVEMENT.  THIS CAUSED THE DRAWBAR TO FAIL AND SUBSEQUENTLY ALLOW THE TRAILER TO FLIP WHEN IT SKIDDED BACK TO THE SHOULDER.  THE TRAILER CAME TO REST BACK ON ITS WHEELS WITH A RUPTURE IN THE RIGHT FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK, ALLOWING JET A FUEL TO ESCAPE.  EMERGENCY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND STATE AND COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS REPORTED TO THE SCENE.  CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL AND THE SUBSEQUENT CLEAN UP BEGAN IMMEDIATELY UNDER THE DIRECT SUPERVISION OF EPA AND DEQ PERSONNEL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATER.

column168: A CAR INSPECTOR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S YEOMAN YARD IN TAMPA, FL, REPORTED AN AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM THE CARS SITTING ON THE REPAIR TRACK. THE TERMINAL MANAGER INSPECTED THE CARS ON THE TRACK.  A PLMX35343, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS THE ONLY AMMONIA SITTING ON THE REPAIR TRACK.  THE TERMINAL MANAGER DID NOT NOTE ANY ODORS.  HE REQUESTED TO HAVE AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INSPECT THE CAR FOR POSSIBLE LEAKS.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT PLMX 35343 WAS LEAKING VAPORS THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD).  THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE BOTTOM O-RING IN THE PRD.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER, AIR PRODUCTS, AND THE CONSIGNEE, YARA, WERE NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS DISCUSSED WITH YARA.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

A SWITCH CREW WORKING IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HOOKERS POINT RAIL YARD IN TAMPA, FL, REPORTED SMELLING A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT CARS IN THE YARD FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THEY DID NOT DETECT ANY AMMONIA ON THEIR MONITORING INSTRUMENT BUT THEY COULD OCCASIONALLY SMELL A SLIGHT AMMONIA ODOR.  THEY INSPECTED THE VALVES AND FITTINGS ON A PLMX35335, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, AND FOUND VAPORS LEAKING THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD).  THEY CONFIRMED THE VAPOR LEAK WITH SOAPY WATER AND COULD ALSO HEAR A SLIGHT HISS FROM THE PRD.  THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED BOTH THE TOP AND THE BOTTOM O-RINGS AND THE RETAINER IN THE PRD.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE BOTTOM O-RING WAS FOUND TO BE PINCHED.  THE SHIPPER, AIR PRODUCTS, AND THE CONSIGNEE, YARA, WERE NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DISCUSSED WITH YARA.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

THE WALTON COUNTY, FL, 911 DISPATCH CENTER REPORTED TO CSX TRANSPORTATION THAT THEY HAD RECEIVED A REPORT FROM A LOCAL CITIZEN OF A STRONG SULFUR/ROTTEN EGG ODOR COMING FROM RAIL CARS SITTING ON A NEARBY RAIL SIDING IN DE FUNIAK SPRINGS, MILEPOST 00K716.85.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT INVESTIGATED AND REPORTED THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A TANK CAR, UTLX 201967, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS, CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE.  THERE WAS NO VISUAL SIGN OF ANY PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, LEAF RIVER CELLULOSE, LLC, A SUBSIDIARY OF KOCH CELLULOSE, THROUGH CHEMTREC.  CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR AND DETERMINE WHERE THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THERE WAS NO VISIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE CAR, HOWEVER, THERE WAS A SPOT OF DRIED RESIDUE AT THE BASE OF THE MANWAY.  ALL 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND 4 OF THE 8 BOLTS WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT.  IN ADDITION, THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS NOT PROPERLY ALIGNED.  THE CONTRACTOR COULD NOT GET THE MANWAY COVER GASKET TO FORM A VAPOR TIGHT SEAL, SO THEY INSTALLED A RUBBER GASKET ON TOP OF THE EXISTING GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE ODOR FADED AWAY.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION. LEAF RIVER CELLULOSE WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE MANWAY WHICH ALLOWED VAPORS TO ESCAPE.

column168: DRIVER LOADED 9,210 GALLONS OF GASOLINE INTO A TRANSPORT TANKER.  HE LEFT THE MARATHON ASHLAND INDIANAPOLIS TERMINAL AND DROVE SOUTH ON MICHIGAN ROAD.  HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO TURN WEST ONTO THE ENTRANCE RAMP OF I-465 WHEN HE OVERDROVE THE INTERSECTION AND DROVE ONTO THE RUMBLE STRIPS THAT SEPARATE THE DRIVING LANES.  HE PROCEEDED WEST ONTO THE RAMP AND THE INERTIA CARRIED HIM OFF THE CONCRETE RAMP AND INTO THE GRASS BERM ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE RAMP.  ONCE THE WHEELS WERE OFF THE PAVEMENT, THE TRACTOR/TANK ROLLED OVER.  IT APPEARS THE T/T MADE ALMOST ONE COMPLETE ROLL OVER AND THEN ROLLED BACK TO THE NORTH OR ONTO THE T/T PASSENGER SIDE WHERE IT CAME TO REST.  THE PIKE TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE MARION COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPT.  THE FIRE DEPT. TOLD ME THEY HAD MADE ALL PROPER NOTIFICATIONS AND HAD APPLIED PLUG AND DIKE TO THE LAST COMPARTMENT THAT WAS LEAKING GASOLINE AND APPLIED A PATCH KIT TO A SERVICE TUBE IN COMPARTMENT #1.  THEY ALSO NOTIFIED SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA WHO RESPONDED AND PARTICIPATED IN THE CLEAN UP.  THE FIRE DEPT.  PLACED BOOMS, PEAT SORB AND FOAM TO THE AREA.  THE TANKER LEAKED SLOWLY FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES DUE TO WELDED SEAMS BETWEEN THE FOUR COMPARTMENTS.  THE TANKER WAS THEN PUMPED OFF BY CUTTING HOLES IN EACH COMPARTMENT AND VACUUMING OUT THE GASOLINE.  MOST OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST AFTER THE TANKER WAS RIGHTED AND THE GASOLINE ESCAPED FROM THE VOID AREAS OF THE TANKER COMPARTMENTS. SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT DUE TO DRIVER ERROR AND CARELESS DRIVING.
A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED PLASTIC JERRICAN WAS FOUND LEAKING AROUND THE TOP CAP.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED AND THE JERRICAN PLACED IN A STEEL DRUM AND SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ON FRIDAY, AUGUST 20, 2004 AT APPROX. 1630 HOURS THERE WAS A SPILL OF MALATHION CLASS 9 UN3082, AT THE PORT/COOPER-T. SMITH CFS STATION AT BARBOURS CUT.  PORT-COOPER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSLOADING IBC'S OF MALATHION BETWEEN CONTAINERS AND 5 HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM CONTAINER NUMBER SEAU8185840 TO BE CONSOLIDATED AND RELOADED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER.  THESE 5 IBC'S WERE PLACED ON THE LOADING DOCK.  AT THE SAME TIME, LUMBER WAS BEING LOADED INTO OTHER CONTAINERS.  ONE OF PORT-COOPER'S FORKLIFT OPERATORS MOVING THE LUMBER LET HIS LOAD CONTACT ONE OF THE IBC'S AND A SHARP EDGE PUNCTURED THE PLASTIC LINER CAUSING SOME OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT ON TO THE DOCK.  BEFORE THE IBC COULD BE TURNED ONTO ITS SIDE WITH THE HOLE UP, APPROX. 30 GALLONS WERE LOST.  THE AREA OF THE SPILL WAS ISOLATED AND DIKED OFF TO PREVENT SPREAD AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.  PORT OF HOUSTON, FEDERAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES CONTACTED (SEE BELOW).  AND CLEANUP WAS BEGUN.  THE PRODUCT WHICH REMAINED IN THE DAMAGED IBC WAS TRANSFERRED INTO AN EMPTY CONTAINER AND SHIPPED FOR ANALYSIS.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PICKED UP USING ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE AREA AND EQUIPMENT WERE PRESSURE WASHED AND THE WASH WATER WAS LIKEWISE COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE IMMEDIATE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS THE INATTENTION OF THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR.  A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR WAS THE CLOSE PROXIMITY OF THE TWO OPERATIONS.  IN THE FUTURE, EVERY EFFORT SHOULD BE MADE TO SEGREGATE LOADING/UNLOADING OF HAZARDOUS CARGOES FROM OTHER OPERATIONS.

column168: UNIT NOTED LEAKING PLASTIC PELLETS FROM REAR DOORS.  HAZMAT TEAM FOUND UNIT LOADED WITH SUPER-SAKS BANDED TO PALLET WITH ONE WEB STRAP.  ONE SUPERSAK SHIFTED ONTO REAR DOORS AND WAS PUNCTURED BY DOOR HANDLE/LOCK FITTINGS. THE WEB STRAPPING WAS TOO LIGHT-WEIGHT, FLEXIBLE, AND LOOSE TO BRACE THE HEAVY WEIGHT OF CARGO TO PREVENT SHIFTING.  THE CRISS-CROSS FORMATION OF TWO WEB STRAPS AT REAR OF UNIT, FROM FLOOR TO CEILING, WAS INADEQUATE TO KEEP FREIGHT FROM SHIFTING INTO REAR DOORS.

UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, TWENTY-FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A NAIL INSIDE THE TRAILER.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL PLACED THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND CONTAMINATED SOIL INTO TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS, WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED TO DEMENNO KERDOON IN LOS ANGELES, CA FOR DISPOSAL VIA LANDFILL.  THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: DRIVER RAN OFF OF THE ROAD INTO THE MEDIUM TRAILER CAME LOOSE FROM TRACTOR, AND TRAILER OVERTURNED ONTO R/SIDE.  APPROX. 1764 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM DOME LID & VENT LINE ON TOP OF TANKER AS A RESULT OF THE ROLLOVER. TRACTOR REMAINED UPRIGHT FACING THE TRAILER APPROX 50 YARDS IN FRONT OF TRAILER.  SURRY COUNTY HAZMAT RESPONDED, TOOK CHARGE, & SECURED THE SCENE. PRODUCT LEAKED FOR APPROX. 3 HRS, UNTIL HAZMAT FINALLY TIGHTENED THE DOME LID & CLOSED THE VENT LINE.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR IS STILL WORKING WITH THE STATE.  INSURANCE CARRIER GREAT WEST HAS LAWYERS INVOLVED DUE TO THE EXCESSIVE CLEAN-UP.  I WILL UPDATE THE CLEAN-UP COST WHEN AVAILABLE.

ON MONDAY 8/23 I LEFT ICC AROUND 11:00 AM.  I HAD DELIVERIES TO MAKE IN BRIGHTON AND HENDERSON, COLORADO.  I WAS GOING EAST ON I-76. WHEN I APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF I-25 I MOVED OVER TO THE LEFT LANE TO ALLOW TRAFFIC TO MERGE.  JUST BEFORE THE 74TH AVE EXIT, I NOTICED AND BLUE VAN/TRUCK BEHIND ME WITH IT'S 4 WAY FLASHERS ON.  I DIDN'T KNOW THE REASON FOR THIS.  SO WHEN I WAS ABLE.  I MOVED TO THE RIGHT LANE.  THE TRUCK SHUT IT'S FLASHERS OFF AND PASSED ME.  THIS MADE ME NOTICE THAT I WAS LEAKING SOMETHING.  I WANTED TO GET OFF THE HIGHWAY, BUT WAS UNABLE TO, DUE TO THE CONCRETE BARRIERS ON BOTH SIDES.  AFTER ABOUT 1/2 MILE I WAS ABLE TO PULL OVER, OFF THE SHOULDER, ONTO THE DIRT.  AS SOON AS I EXITED THE TRUCK, THE HCL FUMES WERE VERY STRONG.  I CALLED RICH (BOSS) ON RADIO TO LET HIM KNOW. I THEN PUT OUT MY EMERGENCY TRIANGLES.  AS SOON AS I FINISHED THAT, THE ADAMS COUNTY FIRE CREW WAS ON SCENE.

column168: WHILE DRIVING SOUTH ON SOUTHEAST 2ND STREET ON ONTARIO, OR I TURNED RIGHT ON SOUTHEAST 12TH AVE. AND HEARD A THUMP LIKE SOMETHING FELL IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  I PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, NEXT TO THE MURAKAMI SHEDS AND GOT OUT TO CHECK ON WHAT MADE THE NOISE.  WHEN I OPENED THE DOOR I SAW TWO GP 55S LAYING ON THE FLOOR.  UPON ENTERING THE BACK OF THE TRUCK I SMELLED ACETYLENE AND KNEW I NEEDED TO WORK FAST TO UPRIGHT THE GP'S.  I TURNED THE FIRST ONE AROUND AND DRAGGED IT TO THE REAR TO USE THE LIFT-GATE TO STAND IT UPRIGHT.  AFTER GETTING THE FIRST GP STOOD UP I RETURNED TO GET THE SECOND ONE AND WHILE REACHING FOR THE RING TO DRAG IT OUT I KICKED THE ELECTRONIC SCALE AND HEARD A SMALL EXPLOSION WHICH IGNITED A STRAP.  I RETURNED TO THE CAB AND GOT THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO PUT THE FIRE OUT. WHEN I GOT BACK TO THE FIRE IT HAD PROGRESSED UP THE STRAP TO THE WALL AND ALSO IGNITED SOME PAPER WORK.  USING THE EXTINGUISHER I PUT OUT THE STRAP AND PAPER, THEN NOTICED A SMALL FLAME ON TOP OF THE GP.  I POINTED THE EXTINGUISHER AT THAT FLAME AND REALIZED THE EXTINGUISHER WAS EMPTY.  WITH NO OTHER RECOURSE FOR FIRE CONTAINMENT I EXITED THE TRUCK FOR THE LAST TIME AND RAN FOR HELP.  I FOUND A GENTLEMAN WITH A CELL PHONE AND SPOKE WITH 911 DISPATCH UNTIL THE POLICE ARRIVED.

A NEXAIR, LLC DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO A CUSTOMER LOCATION TO RETRIEVE AN "EMPTY" 150 LB CHLORINE CYLINDER.  THE CYLINDER WAS LOADED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE NEXAIR FACILITY AT PINEVILLE, LA.  AS THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE CYLINDER, THERE WAS EVIDENCE OF A VERY STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE VALVE AREA OF THE CYLINDER.  BECAUSE OF THE STRONG ODOR AND THE SEVERELY CORRODED CONDITION AROUND THE VALVE AREA OF THE CYLINDER, THE FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT/HAZMAT TEAM SECURED THE CYLINDER USING A CHLORINE "A" K.T. ALLIED UNIVERSAL WHO IS THE OWNER OF THE CYLINDER, WAS NOTIFIED AND THE DISPATCHED A TRUCK AND PERSONNEL TO RETRIEVE THE CYLINDER THE NEXT DAY. ALL NEXAIR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN CAUTIONED ABOUT TRANSPORTING CORRODED, DAMAGED OR DEFECTIVE CYLINDERS.  AS ANOTHER PREVENTATIVE MEASURE, THE NEXAIR SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND SAFETY TEAM HAS RECOMMENDED TO NEXAIR OWNERS AND MANAGEMENT THAT NEXAIR REFRAIN FROM SALES AND DISTRIBUTION OF ALL POISON GASES/INHALATION HAZARDS.  THIS RECOMMENDATION IS UNDER CONSIDERATION AT THIS TIME.

ONLY THING HE COULD CONCLUDE WAS THAT THERE WAS SOME TYPE OF FAILURE ON ONE OF THE BOTTOM SEAMS OF THE DRUM. WHILE UNLOADING DRUMS FROM TRAILER FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED ONE OF THE DRUMS WITH HIS FORKBLADES SPILLING OVER HALF THE CONTENTS IN THE TRAILER. THIS WAS A DIRECT RESULT OF THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR NOT PAYING ATTENTION TO HIS CLEARANCES.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS DISCIPLINED AND RETRAINED ON FORKLIFT TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURENCES.

column168: AT THE DOCK, AN UNLOADER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO BEGIN STRIPPING A PICK UP TRAILER.  HE ENCOUNTERED AN ESCAPE OF A LARGE QUANTITY OF LIQUID. INVESTIGATION BY THE DOCK SUPERVISOR DISCLOSED THAT A DRUM OF H/M HAD BEEN PUNCTURED ON ITS BOTTOM BY A WASHER THAT WAS ON EDGE.  THE DRUM HAD BEEN LOADED AT THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER.  THE SUPERVISOR BELIEVES THAT THE WASHER HAD BEEN LYING FLAT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR DURING LOADING.  DURING TRANSIT, THE DRUM AND THE WASHER BOUNCED UP, ALLOWING THE WASHER TO STAND ON END OF AN INSTANT.  AS THE DRUM CAME DOWN, IT LANDED ON THE END OF THE WASHER, PUNCTURING THE DRUM.  A 1/2" HOLE RESULTED ALLOWING ESCAPE OF ABOUT 2/3 OF THE DRUM'S CONTENTS.  THE WASHER WAS STILL IMPALED IN THE DRUM WHEN THE SUPERVISOR OBSERVED IT.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT OIL DRY ONTO THE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER, ON THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER AND ON THE DOCK FLOOR.  THE SUPERVISOR REPORTS THAT ALL OF THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND THAT NONE OF IT HAD MIGRATED TO ANY WATERWAY ACCESS POINT.  AFTER ALL OF THE SPILLAGE HAD BEEN ABSORBED, THE OIL DRY WAS SHOVELED UP AND PUT INTO TWO DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE PUT IN THE HAZMAT AREA TO BE HELD FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON SR 24 IN THE VICINITY OF NEW HAVEN, INDIANA PULLING A 7,000 GALLONS TANKER.  THERE WAS ANOTHER INCIDENT ON SR 24 BLOCKING TRAFFIC.  HE FOLLOWED TRUCKS TO DETOUR THE TRAFFIC BACKUP AND TURNED LEFT ONTO BRUICK ROAD AND THEN ATTEMPTED TO TURN RIGHT ONTO BREMER ROAD.  AFTER STOPPING AT THE STOP SIGN, THE DRIVER PULLED INTO THE INTERSECTION AS FAR AS POSSIBLE BEFORE MAKING HIS TURN.  DURING THE TURN THE TRAILER SHIFTED, POSSIBLY DUE TO THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY FAILING, THE SHIFTED WEIGHT OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TANKER PULLED THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR INTO THE DITCH.  THE DRIVER CALLED 911 FROM HIS VEHICLE AND INFORMED THEM OF THE INCIDENT.  THE LOCAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED PLACING PANS UNDER THE LEAKING DOME COVER.  LATER PSC CONTRACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS ARRIVED AND DECONTAMINATED THE AREA.  THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN THE DRIVER AND NORTRU TRANSPORTATION GROUP WAS TERMINATED.

THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP;  IT DID NOT MIGRATE OFF OF THE PAVEMENT.  THE MANAGER JOHN BELEDA NOTIFIED THE APPROPRIATE PARTIES OF THE OCCURRENCE.  IT WAS LEARNED AFTERWARD THAT COMPARTMENT #2 HAD A CAPACITY OF ONLY 2900 GALLONS.

column168: ON 08/07/04 OUR DRIVER, JAMES RILEY CALLED FROM THE TERMINAL TO ADVISE HE HAD A DRUM LEAKING TOWARDS THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DARK AND HE COULD NOT DETERMINE WHERE THE MATERIALS WAS COMING FROM.  HE WAS ADVISED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK SURROUNDING THE DRUM NO MATERIALS WAS TRAVELING OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER OR ANY OTHER PLACE IN THE TRAILER.  TALKED TO UNIVAR USA AND WAS DETERMINED BY ALL OF US THAT THE BEST THING TO DO WAS WAIT UNTIL THE MORNING TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION.  THE DRIVER SPENT THE NIGHT AT THE TERMINAL IN CANFIELD CHEMTRON WAS SENT OUT BY UNIVAR USA TO CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL AND EVALUTATE THE SITUATION.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 5 OF 5 DRUMS WERE IMPROPERLY SEALED AS NO GASKETS WERE INSIDE THE BUNGS ON THE DRUMS THEREFORE MATERIAL SEEPED BETWEEN THE LID AND THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  DART PROVIDED GASKETS TO CHEMTRON WHO PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPEEDI DRI THE DRIVER HAD PUT DOWN TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL AND RESEALED THE DRUMS FOR SHIPMENT.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS SITUATION FROM OCCURRING AGAIN THE CUSTOMER, UNIVAR USA HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION AND PROPER PACKAGING PROCEDURES.  AS PART OF OUR CONTINUED TRAINING WE WILL ADVISE THE DRIVERS TO CHECK FOR TIGHTNESS O THE BUNGS.

FULL TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN WILLIAM HENDERSON AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN TERRY RUGGERIE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN: 14 X @ 6 OZ OF "EFKA-4080" (MARKED "FLAMMABLE") AND 1 X @ 6 OZ OF "EFKA-2725", ALL IN GLASS BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES THAT WERE SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  TWO OF THE BOTTLES OF "EFKA-4080" WERE BROKEN ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK ENTIRE CONTENTS. THE SHIPPER FAXED US A MSDS CLASSIFYING THE "EFKA-4080" AS "RESIN SOLUTION, 3, UN 1866, PG III" AND THE "EFKA-2725" AS "CYCLOHEXANONE, SOLUTION, 3, UN 1915, PG III".  THIS SHIPMENT ALSO CONTAINED OTHER VARIOUS NON REGULATED "EFKA" PRODUCTS.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN WILMINGTON BY TRUCK ON FLYT# 8111.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  A COPY OF THIS REPORT IS ALSO BEING SENT TO THE OHIO OFFICE OF MOTOR CARRIERS.  THE FULL TIME AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT IS HELD UNTIL PERMISSION TO MARK AND LABEL AND A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IS RECEIVED.  THERE WERE THREE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. PVS CHEMICAL SOLUTIONS OF DETROIT, MICHIGAN ARRANGED FOR A SHIPMENT OF APPROXIMATELY 45,000 LBS. OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION (UN1789) TO BE DELIVERED FROM PPG INDUSTRIES IN BARBERTON, OHIO TO UNIVAR USA, INC. IN TWINSBURG, OHIO.  (SEE ATTACHED SHIPPING PAPERS).  ON AUGUST 11, 2004, THE TRUCKING COMPANY DELIVERED THIS SHIPMENT TO UNIVAR USA. WITH NO ROADWAY INCIDENTS OCCURRING WHILE THE SHIPMENT WAS IN TRANSIT.  HOWEVER, DURING PRODUCT UNLOADING, UNIVAR USA, INC.'S ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK FAILED AND THE UNIVAR USA TANK RUPTURED CAUSING SOME HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO EXCEED SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AT THE UNIVAR USA FACILITY.  (SEE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER INCIDENT REPORT #731685 AND OHIO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY'S INITIAL POLLUTION INCIDENT REPORT DATE AUGUST 20, 2004).  MIDDOUGH CONSULTING, INC. OF CLEVELAND, OHIO HAS BEEN RETAINED TO INVESTIGATE THIS INCIDENT.  PRELIMINARY OBSERVATIONS ARE AS FOLLOWS:  THE TANK WAS A NON-PRESSURIZED TANK THAT UNIVAR USA PERMITTED TO BECOME PRESSURIZED; THE SCRUBBING COMPONENT OF THE VENTING APPARATUS TO THE UNIVAR USA TANK FAILED TO WORK PROPERLY WHICH IN TURN PERMITTED THE TANK TO BECOME PRESSURIZED; OTHER PROBLEMS WITH THE UNIVAR USA TANK REMAIN UNDER INVESTIGATION.  UNIVAR USA RETAINED CHEMTRON TO PERFORM EMERGENCY SITE REMEDIATION FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT; UNIVAR USA HAS NOT SHARED THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR AMOUNT FOR ITS CLEANUP EFFORTS.  AN EVACUATION OF LOCAL BUSINESSES WITHIN ONE MILE OF THE UNIVAR USA FACILITY OCCURRED FOLLOWING THE EVENT.  (SEE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER INCIDENT REPORT #731685).  THE AREA SURROUNDING THE UNIVAR USA FACILITY WAS SECURED BY US EPA, OHIO EPA AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS. THE TRUCKING COMPANY HAS FULLY COOPERATED WITH ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL GOVERNMENT REQUESTS FOR INFORMATION REGARDING THIS MATTER.

column168: A PRIORITY PARCEL SHIPMENT TENDERED BY DHL EXPRESS WAS ACCEPTED IN SAN FRANCISCO UNDER AIR WAYBILL 001SFO4761341.  THE SPILL DISCOVERED IN THE F1 FORWARD CARGO COMPARTMENT AT OFF LOAD IN MIAMI.  THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED ON FLIGHT 652 A 737 AIRCRAFT TAIL NUMBER 3CM, AND FOUND BY FLEET SERVICE CREW OF FOUR (HARRIS, MORALES, DAVIS, BOWERS) WHO CONTACTED THEIR IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR.  ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR MICHAEL BAUSH, AND MIAMI'S LEAD ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR ALLEN WECKBACH ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND CONTACTED METRO DADE FIRE DEPARTMENT'S HAZMAT TEAM TO RESPOND.  THE LEAD EC CONTACTED THE CARGO DEPARTMENT IN ORDER TO OBTAIN INFORMATION ON THE SHIPPER AND DESCRIPTION OF THE MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED BY REQUESTING A MATERIAL DATA SAFETY SHEET (MSDS) FROM THE SHIPPER.  LABELING ON THE PACKAGE DESCRIBED THE CONTENTS AS DMPAT 30% THE VERIFICATION FROM THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER DESCRIBED THE CHEMICAL NAME AS O, O-DIMETHYL PHOSPHOROAMIDOTHIOATE DMPAT, BOTH A CORROSIVE AND TOXIC SUBSTANCE.  HAZMAT AND METRO DADE PARAMEDICS AS WELL AS AA MEDICAL ASSESSED AND RELEASED THE FOUR FLEET SERVICE CREWMEMBERS THAT DISCOVERED THE SPILL.  EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO DECONTAMINATED THE AIRCRAFT AND GROUND SERVICE EQUIPMENT (BELT LOADER, BAGGAGE CART).  AA AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE WAS ABLE TO REVIEW AND REPAIR THE FORWARD F1 CARGO COMPARTMENT THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL ALSO PREPARED THE SPILLED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  AMERICAN AIRLINES CARGO IS INVESTIGATING AND REVIEWING THE INSPECTION PLAN FOR DHL EXPRESS AS WELL AS ALL SHIPMENTS TENDERED BY DHL EXPRESS IN SAN FRANCISCO.

CONSIGNEE BEING SO CLOSE TO THE SITE RESPONDED IN MUTUAL AID AND WITH THE HELP OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TIGHTENED THE FITTINGS (BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE REQUIRED 1/2 TURN TO THE TOP OPERATING HANDLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP REQUIRED 1/4 TURN TO SECURE THAT CLOSURE).  BY 15:00 THE TANK CAR'S LEAKS HAD BEEN STOPPED AND FITTING AND CLOSURE TIGHTENED.  (2) IT WAS OBVIOUS THAT A COMPLETE AND THOROUGH INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR WAS NOT DONE AND STRICTER SHIPPING INSPECTION WITH A BETTER CHECKLIST SHOULD BE PUT INTO EFFECT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 8-12-04 OUR CREW WAS TRAVELING ON CONVOY GOING EAST ON 553 IN PENN RUN. AT ABOUT 0220 THE ACID TRUCK WENT OFF THE ROAD AT THE CURVE IN FRONT OF THE PENN RUN FIRE CO.  THE TRUCK WENT OVER SOME TREE STUMPS AND LANDED WITH THE BACK OF THE TRUCK TAKING OUT A CORNER OF A HORSE STALL.  THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT HAS NOT YET BEEN DETERMINED.  WE HAVE NOT RECEIVED THE POLICE REPORT YET.  THE DRIVERS IN FRONT OF THE ACID TRUCK REPORTED SEEING A WHITE VAN GOING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION AND ESTIMATED THAT THE VAN WOULD HAVE BEEN AT THE CURVE THE SAME TIME AS THE ACID TRUCK.  BUT THE DRIVERS AFTER HIM DIDN'T SEE A WHITE VAN.  THE DOT OFFICER INSPECTED THE TRUCK FOR PROBLEMS AND NO PROBLEMS WERE NOTED.  THE TRUCK PASS THE INSPECTION.  AT THE TIME THE ACCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED THE DRIVER WAS STILL TRAPPED IN THE TRUCK BEEN HELD UP BY HIS SEAT BELT.  THE FIRST THING OUR DRIVERS DID ALONG WITH FIRE PERSONAL AND RESIDENTS WERE TO REMOVE OUR DRIVER A.S.A.P.  AFTER 20 MINUTES THE DRIVER WAS OUT OF THE TRUCK.  THE REASON THEY FOCUSED ON THE DRIVER IS BECAUSE THE TANK RUPTURED AND THERE WAS AND FUMES ALL AROUND THE DRIVER.  WHEN THE ACID TRUCK WENT OVER THE TREE STUMPS THE 3 IBC TANKS MADE OF POLYETHYLENE BURST OPEN CAUSING AN IMMEDIATE RELEASE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  WHEN THE TRUCK FINALLY CAME TO A STOP THE BACK OF THE TRUCK LANDED ON THE CORNER OF A HORSE STALL, WHICH TOTALLY DESTROYED THE LAST TANK.  THE TRUCK LANDED ON ITS PASS SIDE, WHICH ALSO ATTRIBUTED TO THE IMMEDIATE RELEASE OF THE ACID.  THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING A TOTAL OF 1000 GALLONS OF 28% HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE FIRST 2 TANKS HAD 375 GALLONS AND THE LAST HAD 250 GALLONS.  ALL BUT 50 GALLONS WAS RELEASED ON TO THE GROUND.  WE ONLY HAD 500 LBS OF SODA ASH AT THE YARD, WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SCENE AND SPREAD ON THE GROUND TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  MCCUTCHEON ENTERPRISES BROUGHT THE REST AND DID THE FINAL CLEAN UP.

FILE: 3750 D, SHIPPER: FELLOWSHIP HALL, AWB#: GSO 1042706910 PVD.  ON 08.28.04 AT 0030 AN INSIDE LEAKING LAB PACK WAS REPORTED IN "A" BUILDING (EXPRESS AREA, LATERAL 30) OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN URSEL WEBB DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A PLASTIC LAB PACK WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE INNER PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THE LAB PACK FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THE LAB PACK TO CONTAIN 10 CLEAR PLASTIC BAGS THAT EACH CONTAINED A PLASTIC SPECIMEN CUP.  EACH SPECIMEN CUP HAD A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE THAT WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURES ON THE CUPS CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ OF THEIR CONTENTS.  THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE LAB PACK.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN ILN ON FLIGHT #0189, TAIL 973AX.  THIS LAB PACK WAS MARKED "OVERWRAP FOR DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN SHIPMENTS".  AS A PRECAUTION, THE AREA INVOLVED WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED WITH BLEACH BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN SEALED AND BAGGED THE LAB PACK IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0033  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

SEE ATTACHED ACCIDENT REPORT AND PICTURES.

CSX TRANSPORTATION ROAD FREIGHT Q47720 WAS STOPPED AT MOSES ROAD (SE300.2) IN COPOL, NORTH CAROLINA.  PRIVATE CITIZEN DAWN STONE STATES THAT SHE WAS WALKING ALONG TRAIN AND NOTED FRESH LIQUID ON SIDE OF TANK CAR GATX33805 (LOAD - SULFURIC ACID).  FOR SOME UNKNOWN REASON, SHE REACHED OUT AND WIPED THE LIQUID WITH HER HAND.  IMMEDIATELY, SHE REACHED A WATER SOURCE AND WASHED HER HANDS OFF, THEN CONTACTED THE ROBESON COUNTY 911 DISPATCHER. ROBESON COUNTY DISPATCHED EMERGENCY SERVICE PERSONNEL TO THE SITE.  THE EMERGENCY SERVICE TECHNICIANS MET WITH MS. STONE AND EXAMINED HER HAND(S). NO SIGNS OF CHEMICAL BURNS NOTED.  THE EMT'S WASHED OFF HER HAND(S) AND SHE DEPARTED THE SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDERNEATH THE TANK CAR TO COLLECT THE DRIPPING SULFURIC ACID.  CSX TRANSPORTATION CONTACTED HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE TANK CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL, HEPACO'S REPRESENTATIVE FOUND THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE TO BE A BLOWN 165 POUND FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED.  AFTER COMPLETION, THE TRAIN DEPARTED TO IT'S FINAL DESTINATION TO HAMLET, NORTH CAROLINA.

column168: AT APPROX. 12 NOON ON THURSDAY AUG. 5TH, ART DUIM RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE WAREHOUSE STATING THAT WE HAD A LEAKING IBC OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID INSIDE A TRAILER AT OUR DOCK.  WITH ART AT THE TIME WERE G. MARTIN, TIM DEAL, AND MIKE NORRIS.  ALL 4 RESPONDED TO CALL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INCIDENT SITE, IT WAS APPARENT THAT THERE WAS LIQUID LEAKING FROM UNDERNEATH A 53' "THUNDERBIRD PACIFIC" TRAILER FROM THE FRONT ALL THE WAY TO THE BACK. THERE WAS A VISIBLE VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER INTO THE WAREHOUSE.  THE TEMPERATURE WAS APPROX. 90 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT, THE SKY WAS CLEAR AND THERE WAS A SLIGHT BREEZE COMING FROM THE SOUTH WEST.  GEORGE MARTIN NOTIFIED CHARLY BONNIE, BRIAN RINEHART, AND MIKE NASSRALLA.  MIKE MORRIS CONTACTED ECOLOGY CONTROL INDUSTRIES (ECI) TO COME AND HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP.  THE INCIDENT SITE WAS ISOLATED, ALL ROLL UP DOORS LEADING TO AND FROM BUILDING 4A WERE CLOSED TO PREVENT FURTHER VAPOR CONTAMINATION OF THE WAREHOUSE, AND TO ALLOW THE AIR EXCHANGE SYSTEM AT THE FACILITY TO EVACUATE THE FUMES.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PUT DOWN AROUND THE TRAILER AND THE GATE VALVE ON THE STORM WATER CHANNEL (APPROX 200') THAT RUNS ALONG THE WEST SIDE OF THE FACILITY WAS CLOSED TO PREVENT THE MIGRATION OF HCL OFF-SITE. DESPITE THE CLOSING OF THE ROLL UP DOORS IN BUILDING 4A, VAPORS HAD SPREAD THROUGHOUT MUCH OF THE FACILITY.  WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED AND ONLY LIMITED WORK WAS ALLOWED IN THE TANK FARM, AND BUILDING 1 & 2 OF THE WAREHOUSE WHICH HAD NOT BEEN AFFECTED.  CARLOS ZEPEDA, OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR FOR ECI ARRIVED AT 1:45 P.M. TO ASSES THE SITUATION, HE EXPLAINED THAT HE HAD A CREW ON STAND-BY UNTIL HE WAS SURE WHAT WAS NEEDED. CARLOS AND MIKE MORRIS DISCUSSED THE CLEAN UP PROCESS, CARLOS SPOKE WITH ECI'S DISPATCHER AND AT 2:55 P.M. THE BALANCE OF THE CREW ARRIVED.  6 HAZ-MAT TECHNICIANS, 1 FIELD CHEMIST, AND CARLOS MADE UP THE RESPONSE TEAM. AFTER A SHORT TAIL GATE SAFETY BRIEFING, THE CLEAN UP COMMENCED AROUND 3:15 P.M   AFTER DONNING LEVEL "B" PPE, A SLURRY OF SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE STANDING ACID IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN RINSED DOWN WITH WATER WHICH WAS CAPTURED BY THE STORM WATER CHANNEL.  THE NOW EMPTY TOTE WAS REMOVED AS WELL AS THE 10 EMPTY DRUMS AND 1 TOTE OF PROPYLENE GLYCOL THAT WAS ALSO ON THE TRAILER.  ALL ITEMS REMOVED WERE DE-CONTAMINATED AND SET IN THE WAREHOUSE.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN NEUTRALIZED A SECOND TIME WITH A BICARB-SLURRY AND RINSED.  THE CREW THEN MOVED OUTSIDE TO THE DOCK AREA AND AFTER DOWN GRADING TO LEVEL "C" PPE, PROCEEDED TO NEUTRALIZE AND RINSE THE CONCRETE AREA.  ALL RINSATE WAS CONTAINED IN THE STORM WATER CHANNEL AND A PUMP WAS SET UP AT THE GATE VALVE, 200' DOWNSTREAM, TO PUMP THE MATERIAL INTO TOTES.  AT APPROX. 4:30 MICHAEL NASSRALLA NOTIFIED THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES (OES), AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  LA COUNTY FIRE STATED THEY WERE SENDING SOMEONE OVER AS A PRECAUTION.  LA COUNTY HEALTH & HAZ-MAT DIS

A TRAINMAN AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RICE YARD IN WAYCROSS, GA, REPORTED THAT HE DETECTED AN AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM AROUND A NEARBY TANK CAR, TJRX20455, LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, AND REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CAR AND REPORTED THAT HE DID NOT DETECT ANY AMMONIA ODOR ON THE GROUND AROUND THE CAR.  HOWEVER, WHEN HE INSPECTED DOME ON TOP OF THE CAR, HE NOTED A SLIGHT AMMONIA ODOR WHEN HE OPENED AN INSPECTION PORT ON THE DOME.  TJRX20455 WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CHECK THE VALVES AND FITTINGS INSIDE THE DOME.  THE TRAINMAN, MR. DA HUNT, WAS TAKEN TO THE SATILLA REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER FOR OBSERVATION.  CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTACTED ITS INDUSTRIAL HYGENE CONSULTANT AND THEY CONFERRED WITH THE EMERGENCY ROOM PHYSICIAN.  MR. HUNT WAS OBSERVED, TESTED AND RELEASED WITH NO TREATMENT OR MEDICATIONS AND WAS APPROVED TO RETURN TO DUTY.  CSXT'S RESPONSE CONTRACTOR CHECKED THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK AND FOUND IT WAS NORMAL.  THEY INSPECTED THE VALVES AND FITTINGS IN THE DOME AND DISCOVERED A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK COMING FROM THE MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE SLIP TUBE.  THE VAPOR LEAK COULD NOT BE REPAIRED.  THE GAUGING DEVICE CAP WAS TIGHTENED DOWN AND THE RELEASE TO ATMOSPHERE STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER, TERRA INTERNATIONAL, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE LEAK COULD NOT BE REPAIRED UNDER LOAD.  TERRA INTERNATIONAL OBTAINED AN FRA APPROVAL, FRA-04080230, TO MOVE THE CAR TO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING.

TANK CAR PPTX3341, A LOADED TANK CAR OF MOLTEN SULFUR WAS REPORTED AS EMITTING AN ODOR FROM THE MANWAY AREA.  CSX HAZMAT FIELD SERVICES MANAGER, JIM BRISKI, RESPONDED TO THE DANVILLE, ILLINOIS, CSX RAILYARD AND FOUND A SULFUR ODOR EVIDENT FROM A THREE INCH LOADING PIPE ATTACHED TO THE MANWAY COVER.  MR BRISKI REMOVED THE PIPE, CLEANED THE THREADS, APPLIED TEFLON TAPE AND REINSTALLED THE PIPE.  NO ODOR WAS NOTED AFTER THE REPAIR WAS MADE AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT.

column168: THE DRIVER APPARENTLY FORGOT TO UNHOOK THE FLY HOSE AND DROVE ABOUT 20 MILES ON PUBLIC HWYS SPILLING FUEL ALL THE WHILE.  THE MOST FUEL SPILLED WAS AT THE INITIAL SITE AND WHERE THE TRUCK FINALLY CAME TO A STOP.  THERE MAY HAVE BEEN SOME ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT AS SOME OF THE PRODUCT WAS FOUND IN THE SCIOTO RIVER DRAINAGE SYSTEM.  THE HWYS AND ROADS WERE SANDED ACCORDING TO OHIO DOT SPOKESMAN RUSS DECKER.  MIKE GERBER FROM OHIO EPA 419-351-4987 WAS ALSO ON THE SITE AND WORKED WITH INTERDYNE ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSESS THE IMPACT OF THE SPILL.  WARREN FOX OF ECS COORDINATED WITH INTERDYNE AND STAYED ABREAST OF THE SPILL CLEANUP.  SEVERAL CALLS WERE RECEIVED FROM CITIZENS CLAIMING TO HAVE BEEN IMPACTED BY FUEL ON THEIR VEHICLES.  OHIO DOT SPILL CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AND TODD TAYLOR WAS THE OFFICER IN CHARGE. THE KENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT SPREAD SAND AT THE KENTON SITE.  CLINT FROM INTERDYNE WAS COORDINATOR FOR THE COMPANY 419-236-3339.  FURTHER WORK RELATING TO THIS PILL WILL BE DETERMINED DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS ON SUNDAY 8/29/04.

column168: THIS INCIDENT INVOLVED A HIGHWAY ACCIDENT THAT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 AM ON AUGUST 27, 2004, ON INTERSTATE 94 AT APPROXIMATELY MILE MARKER 4.5 IN NEW BUFFALO TOWNSHIP, MICHIGAN.  AN ON-TRACK TRUCKING TRACTOR TRAILER STRUCK A TST EXPEDITED SERVICES INC. VEHICLE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTING TWO STEEL TOTES CONTAINING YELLOW PAINT.  THE IMPACT BY THE ON-TRACK TRUCKING VEHICLE CAUSED PRODUCT TO BREACH THE TOTES.  TST EXPEDITED SERVICES INC. IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THIS INCIDENT TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (INCIDENT #733233).  THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS TO THIS ACCIDENT WERE THE NEW BUFFALO TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT, BERRIEN COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, MICHIGAN STATE POLICE, MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, AND YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL. TST EXPEDITED SERVICES, INC., RETAINED YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF GRAND RAPIDS, MICHIGAN TO PERFORM COMPREHENSIVE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND SITE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES AT THE IMPACTED SITE FROM AUGUST 27, 2004, THROUGH SEPTEMBER 8, 2004.  THE REMEDIATION WORK WAS PERFORMED WITH COOPERATION FROM MR. JOHN VOLLMER AND MS. LORRAINE THOMAS OF THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  ACCORDING TO MR. column168: THIS INCIDENT INVOLVED A HIGHWAY ACCIDENT THAT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 AM ON AUGUST 27, 2004, ON INTERSTATE 94 AT APPROXIMATELY MILE MARKER 4.5 IN NEW BUFFALO TOWNSHIP, MICHIGAN.  AN ON-TRACK TRUCKING TRACTOR TRAILER STRUCK A TST EXPEDITED SERVICES INC. VEHICLE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTING TWO STEEL TOTES CONTAINING YELLOW PAINT.  THE IMPACT BY THE ON-TRACK TRUCKING VEHICLE CAUSED PRODUCT TO BREACH THE TOTES.  TST EXPEDITED SERVICES INC. IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THIS INCIDENT TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (INCIDENT #733233).  THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS TO THIS ACCIDENT WERE THE NEW BUFFALO TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT, BERRIEN COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, MICHIGAN STATE POLICE, MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, AND YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL. TST EXPEDITED SERVICES, INC., RETAINED YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF GRAND RAPIDS, MICHIGAN TO PERFORM COMPREHENSIVE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND SITE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES AT THE IMPACTED SITE FROM AUGUST 27, 2004, THROUGH SEPTEMBER 8, 2004.  THE REMEDIATION WORK WAS PERFORMED WITH COOPERATION FROM MR. JOHN VOLLMER AND MS. LORRAINE THOMAS OF THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  ACCORDING TO MR. VOLLMER'S INCIDENT REPORTED TITLED PAIN SPILL ON I-94 AT NEW BUFFALO ON AUGUST 27, 2004, THE INCIDENT DID NOT IMPACT WETLANDS NOR DID THE INCIDENT IMPACT THE GALLIEN RIVER. SUMMARY OF EVENTS: #1 UNLOADED BY KRAFT EMPLOYEES.  THE MATERIAL WAS IN A PORTABLE TOTE.  WHEN THE DRIVERS WERE READY TO LEAVE, THEY NOTICED MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR.  #1 CALLED FROM STREET TO ASK HOW TO CLEAN THIS UP AND DISPATCH COMPLETED A HAZARD REPORT.  PAG PAGED AT 13:00 13:05 CALLED CHEMTELL AT 800-255-3924.  TOOK INFO AND WAS GETTING THE MSDS.  13:15 CALLED SHIPPER.  AT 513-874-9700 AND WAS TOLD CAUSTIC SODA WAS USED TO MAKE SOAP AND CAN BE WASHED OUT, NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT.  13:32 CALLED BY CHEMTELL AND TOLD TO USE SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE.  CALLED SHIPPER AND IS NOT BEING TOLD THIS IS A FOOD GRADE AND CAN BE WATERED DOWN BUT TO COLLECT IT IN A DRUM.  SINCE OUR DRIVERS DO NOT HAVE ANY TYPE OF SPILL KITS, I WILL NEED TO EITHER CALL A CLEAN UP CREW OR SEND THEM BACK TO THE CONSIGNEE. SHIPPER CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE AND WE WERE TOLD TO RETURN TO THE CONSIGNEE OR ASK FOR TIM HODGES.  HE WILL ENSURE THE SPILL IS CLEANED UP PROPERLY. END TIME 14:00.

column168: DARRYL OBSERVED SMOKE WHEN HE MAKING A DELIVERY AND RETURNED TO TWINSBURG TO HAVE IT FIXED.  JEFF LUNDSTROM AND GERRY COLOMBO WENT INTO THE TRAILER, REMOVED THE CAPS AND PUT A NEW CAP ON BOTH TOTES.  GERRY AND JEFF DID NOT OBSERVE ANY FREE LIQUID IN THE TOTES AND DARRYL WAS SENT BACK OUT ON HIS RUN.  JEFF WAS NOT ABLE TO SEE THE DOME DUE TO FUMES FROM THE HCL.  WHEN DARRYL LEFT JEFF AND GERRY BELIEVED THEY REPAIRED THE FUMES WITH NEW CAPS. DARYL MADE 3 OTHER STOPS IN ROUTE TO YOUNG CHEMICAL.  HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY LEAKAGE OR SMOKE DURING THE DELIVERIES.  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT YOUNG DARRYL NOTICED SMOKE IN THE TRAILER AND YOUNG EMPLOYEES WOULD NOT GO ON THE TRAILER.  DARRYL CALLED KEVIN THOMAS AS SOON AS HE NOTICED IT LEAKING. WHEN I ARRIVED DARRYL AND I WENT INTO THE TRAILER AND NOTICED THAT TOTE SEEMED TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE LID AGAIN.  WHEN WE TESTED THE LID, WE NOTICED IT WAS VERY LOOSE.  DUE TO THIS BEING THE SECOND TIME WE HAD A LEAK WITH THE SAME TOTE WE DECIDED TO PUMP THE TOTE INTO ANOTHER TOTE.  TIM BAIR ARRIVED AT 2:00, DARRYL AND TIM PULLED EACH TRUCK INTO A TANK TRUCK CONTAINMENT AREA FOR THE TRANSFER.  WE PUMPED THE DAMAGED TOTE FROM THE BOTTOM AND FILLED INTO THE TOP OF THE GOOD TOTE WITH A DIP TUBE. EVERYTHING WAS COMPLETED SUCCESSFULLY WITH NO LEAKS, DRIPS OR SPILLS. CUSTOMER WAS NOT EFFECTED BY THE INCIDENT.  LESS THAN 1 CUP OF HCL LEAKED FROM THE TOTE ON TO THE FLOOR.  THE FLOOR WAS DRIED WITH OIL DRY AND RETURNED TO UNIVAR FOR DISPOSAL.

SIMMONS ARRIVED, HE PERFORMED AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE B-END LIQUID VALVE. PROX 14141 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING SULFURIC ACID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MR SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH KEVIN HOLLANDER, YARDMASTER, WHO ADVISED IT APPEARED THE LEAK WAS FROM THE VENT CAP ON THE CAR AND THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN PLACED IN A SECURE AREA OF THE YARD.  MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED JIM YORK, MATERIALS MANAGER FOR THE CONSIGNEE, EXIDE BATTERY, IN SALINA TO DETERMINE IF THEY HAD SOMEONE THAT COULD RESPOND TO CHECK THE CAR, BUT THEY DID NOT HAVE ANYONE AVAILABLE.  MR. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO SALINA TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE TANK CAR.  ON ARRIVAL, MR SEKAVEC OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID STILL DRIPPING FROM THE FITTING ON THE TOP OF THE CAR BUT NONE FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VENT AREA.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE CAP ON THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE WAS NOT HAND TIGHT. MR. SEKAVEC  BLED THE PRESSURE OFF OF THE CAR AND VERIFIED THAT IT WAS NOT OVERLOADED.  HE THEN TIGHTENED THE CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE AND RESECURED THE AIR LINE PLUG AND VALVE.  FINALLY HE USED APPROXIMATELY EIGHT GALLONS OF BAKING SODA SOLUTION TO DECONTAMINATE THE CAR.  STEVE ROWE, FLEET MANAGER WITH THE SHIPPER (NORFALCO) AND JIM YORK WERE BOTH CONTACTED TO ADVISE THEM OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  MR. YORK WAS ALSO ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN DECONTAMINATED IN THE FIELD BUT THAT SOME RESIDUAL ACID MAY STILL BE PRESENT ON THE CAR.
UNDECLARED LEAKING PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.
AT TIME OF UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION, IT WAS NOTICED THAT A SKID WAS STACKED ON TOP OF THESE 5 GALLON CONTAINER CRUSHING THEM AND CAUSING A LEAK.  THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED ENTIRE SHIPMENT.
